<div id="comment_64422722" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64422722" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64422722" name="comment_link_64422722" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23301612&amp;cid=64422722" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64422722)" >start by implementing dynamic line rating</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64422722" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64422722); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Another+Random+Kiwi">Another Random Kiwi</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Another+Random+Kiwi">( 6224294 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64422722"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64422722">We can start increasing the grid capacity at relatively low cost by implementing <a href="https://inl.gov/national-security/dynamic-line-rating/" title="inl.gov">dynamic line rating</a> [inl.gov] - making use of the unused headroom in the transmission/distribution capacity based on actual conditions, instead of the theoretical capacity if conditions were as bad as they'd ever get (low wind, high temperature).  The authors seemed to have used PG&amp;E data for the cost to expand capacity - I don't know if that already incorporates techniques like DLR, or just building new lines.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64422722">

</div>
